        "user": "How does \"EGGF\" differ from a static-site generator with structured data?",
        "assistant": "“EGGF” still isn’t a widely standardized term, so the exact comparison depends on the source. But if we treat **EGGF** as an **evidence/entity-grounded graph framework**, then it differs from a **static-site generator with structured data** in a few important ways.\n\n## Short version\n\nA **static-site generator with structured data** turns files into web pages.\n\nAn **EGGF-style system** represents entities, claims, evidence, sources, and relationships as a graph for retrieval, reasoning, verification, or AI use.\n\n> **Static-site generator = publishing system.**  \n> **EGGF = knowledge/evidence representation system.**\n\n---\n\n| Aspect | EGGF | Static-site generator with structured data |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main purpose | Model knowledge, entities, claims, evidence, relationships | Generate static HTML/CSS/JS pages |\n| Primary output | Graph, API, retrieval index, evidence network, machine-readable knowledge layer | Website pages, RSS feeds, JSON-LD, sitemaps |\n| Primary user | AI systems, search/retrieval pipelines, analysts, applications | Human website visitors, browsers, search engines |\n| Data model | Entity/relation/claim/evidence graph | Markdown, YAML/TOML front matter, templates, collections |\n| Typical tools | Graph databases, vector stores, extraction pipelines, RDF/property graphs, custom APIs | Jekyll, Hugo, Eleventy, Astro, Gatsby, Next.js static export |\n| Knowledge units | Entities, claims, relations, documents, evidence passages, confidence scores | Posts, pages, tags, categories, authors, dates |\n| Dynamic reasoning | Often designed to support querying, inference, retrieval, validation | Usually precomputed at build time |\n| Provenance/evidence | Usually central | Optional; may just include citations or links |\n| Interoperability | Depends on design; may map to RDF/schema.org | Often emits schema.org/JSON-LD for SEO |\n| Update model | Can be continuously updated from documents/data streams | Usually rebuilt when