e an EGGF as a backend.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nDocuments → EGGF evidence graph → generated static website\n```\n\nThe EGGF could store structured claims and evidence, while the static-site generator publishes human-readable pages from that graph.\n\nOr the reverse:\n\n```text\nMarkdown site → extracted structured data → EGGF\n```\n\nA site made with Hugo, Jekyll, or Astro could be processed into an EGGF-style graph for search, AI question answering, or knowledge exploration.\n\n---\n\n## Simple distinction\n\n> A **static-site generator with structured data** is mainly about turning structured content into a website.  \n> An **EGGF** is mainly about representing knowledge, evidence, and relationships in a graph-like form for computation.",
